What is Insertion Sort?
Imagine youâ€™re playing cards, and you are picking them one by one. You want to arrange them in ascending order in your hand.

Whenever you pick a new card, you compare it with the cards already in your hand and insert it at the correct position.

Thatâ€™s exactly how Insertion Sort works! ğŸƒâœ¨

How Insertion Sort Works (Step-by-Step)
Letâ€™s sort this list:
[5, 3, 8, 4, 2]

Step 1: Start with the Second Element

The first element (5) is already sorted âœ…
Take the second element (3) and insert it into the correct position.
Swap 3 and 5 because 3 is smaller.
Step	    List
Start	    [5, 3, 8, 4, 2]
Insert 3	[3, 5, 8, 4, 2]


Step 2: Insert 8

Take the third element (8).
Itâ€™s already in the correct place because 8 > 5.
Step	    List
Insert 8	[3, 5, 8, 4, 2]


Step 3: Insert 4

Compare 4 with 8 â†’ Swap
Compare 4 with 5 â†’ Swap
Compare 4 with 3 â†’ Stop (4 is greater than 3)
Step	    List
Insert 4	[3, 4, 5, 8, 2]


Step 4: Insert 2

Compare 2 with 8 â†’ Swap
Compare 2 with 5 â†’ Swap
Compare 2 with 4 â†’ Swap
Compare 2 with 3 â†’ Swap
Step	List
Insert 2	[2, 3, 4, 5, 8]

ğŸ‰ Sorted List: [2, 3, 4, 5, 8] ğŸ‰


Time Complexity of Insertion Sort

Case	                        Time Complexity
--------------------------      ----------------------
Best Case (Already Sorted)	    O(n)
Average Case	                O(nÂ²)
Worst Case (Reversed Order)	    O(nÂ²)
--------------------------      ----------------------
ğŸ”¹ Good for nearly sorted data âœ…
ğŸ”¹ Slow for large lists âŒ

Key Takeaways
âœ… Good for small datasets
âœ… Stable Sort (Preserves order of equal elements)
